<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
From Latin, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“aranea”">&quot;aranea&quot;</normalizedToken>
refers to a spider host.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
Hosts covered by dense pale yellow mycelium (162D). Sexual morph: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Stromata</emphasis>
stipitate, arising from the host, multiple, cylindrical at the base, slightly enlarged midway to the terminal stipe below the fertile head, moderate yellow (162A-B), 8-12 mm long, 1-3 mm broad. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Fertile head</emphasis>
disc-shaped, upper surface slightly convex, 3-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3.5 mm. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Perithecia</emphasis>
completely immersed, narrowly ovoid, 1000-1400 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
200-350 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, ostiole pale brownish-orange (165B). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Asci</emphasis>
cylindrical, 8-spored, 400-1000 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long, 3.5-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
broad, with cap 2-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
thick. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Ascospores</emphasis>
hyaline, dissociating into 128 part-spores, cylindrical, 2-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Culture characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
Colonies on OA attaining a diam. of 8-10 mm in 21 d, mycelium sparse, white, reverse pale yellow (161C). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Conidia</emphasis>
forming on vegetative hyphae or by microcyclic conidiation, hyaline, clavate to cylindrical, 2-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
Colonies on PDA attaining a diam. of 8-10 mm in 20 d, mycelium sparse, white, reverse pale yellow (161C). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Conidia</emphasis>
forming on vegetative hyphae or by microcyclic conidiation, hyaline, clavate to cylindrical, 2-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="host">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Host.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Spider egg sac.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Specimen was found on the underside of a dicot leaf of a forest plant.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="113" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="113">
Based on natural specimens, 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Po." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Po. araneae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="araneae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Po. araneae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. nelumboides" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelumboides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. nelumboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. novoguineensis" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novoguineensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. novoguineensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by producing fertile heads at the end of the stipes. The perithecia of these species are completely immersed. The ascospores of 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Po." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Po. araneae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="araneae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Po. araneae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. nelumboides" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelumboides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. nelumboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are filamentous, multiseptate ascospores disarticulating into part-spores, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. novoguineensis" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novoguineensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. novoguineensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
produces filiform, whole ascospores. However, 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Po." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Po. araneae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="araneae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Po. araneae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. nelumboides" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelumboides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. nelumboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the size of the perithecia. In 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Po." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Po. araneae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="araneae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Po. araneae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, perithecia are larger than those reported for 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" genus="H." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="H. nelumboides" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelumboides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">H. nelumboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1000-1400 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
200-350 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
vs. 535-545 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
180-190 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphological comparisons of sexual morphs in Hevansia, Jenniferia and Polystromomyces." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/649844D1D32BE234FC567534FADE3ABC" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" tableUuid="649844D1D32BE234FC567534FADE3ABC">2</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mongkolsamrit, Noisripoom, Sakolrak &amp; Himaman" authorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Cordycipitaceae" genus="Polystromomyces" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Polystromomyces araneae" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" rank="species" species="araneae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Polystromomyces araneae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
produces microcycle conidiation from conidia on culture, while the microcyclic sporulation is often seen in discharged ascospores in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luangsa-ard, Mongkolsamrit, Himaman, Thanakitpipattana &amp; Samson" authorityYear="2020" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Metarhizium" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Metarhizium phuwiangense" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="phuwiangense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Metarhizium phuwiangense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Luangsa-ard, Mongkols., Himaman, Thanakitp. &amp; Samson and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luangsa-ard, Samson &amp; Thanakitpipattana" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Hywel-Jones" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Purpureomyces" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Purpureomyces khaoyaiensis" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="khaoyaiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="113">Purpureomyces khaoyaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hywel-Jones) Luangsa-ard, Samson &amp; Thanakitp (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" author="Mongkolsamrit, S" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="113" pagination="171 - 251" refId="B32" refString="Mongkolsamrit, S, Khonsanit, A, Thanakitpipattana, D, Tasanathai, K, Noisripoom, W, Lamlertthon, S, Himaman, W, Houbraken, J, Samson, RA, Luangsa-ard, J, 2020a. Revisiting Metarhizium and the description of new species from Thailand. Studies in Mycology 95: 171 - 251, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" title="Revisiting Metarhizium and the description of new species from Thailand." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.04.001" volume="95" year="2020 a">Mongkolsamrit et al. 2020a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
